  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Written from a Village Sickbed to Liu Zhiyang
  author: Yang Yugong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A thatched cottage, cramped and low—
    smoke and cooking fires drift thick down the walls.
    A hungry child cries out for rice,
    while I lie sick, composing verse.

    The eaves are short; the morning light arrives too early.
    The blinds are thin; the moonlight lingers late.
    My thoughts grow endless, heavy as sickness itself—
    but who among the living could ever know?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Liu Zhiyang (柳致養) was likely an acquaintance or patron of the poet. The poem's structure suggests it was sent as a letter-poem, a common literary form in East Asian poetry.
  - key: ''
    value: The contrast between the harsh domestic realities (hungry child, poverty) and the poet's intellectual pursuits (composing verse while sick) reflects the literati ideal of maintaining cultural refinement despite material hardship.
